-- Chinese Estates says billionaire CEO Lau resigns after court verdict
-- By Elzio Barreto
-- Sun Mar 16, 2014 09:08AM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, March 16 (Reuters) - Real estate developer Chinese Estates Holdings <0127.HK> said on Sunday its Chairman and Chief Executive Joseph Lau has resigned after he was found guilty of bribery and money laundering charges in Macau.

Ming-wai Lau, the 33-year-old son of Joseph Lau, was appointed chairman and acting CEO effective March 14, the company said in a securities filing. The younger Lau was the vice chairman of Chinese Estates and previously worked at Goldman Sachs and hedge fund firm Longview Partners before joining his father's company in 2006.